{"id":14880804,"mediaExerciseId":"01fb5280-a40a-4566-ae36-f5e9102df78c","exerciseName":"9","chapterName":"3","chapterTitle":"Working with Financial Statements","groupId":612275,"groupTitle":"Questions and Problems","isPremium":true,"sectionName":null,"sectionTitle":null,"pageNumber":86,"solutions":[{"id":5959089,"modifiedOn":"2021-01-01T00:00:00.000000","steps":[{"columns":[{"text":"In this problem, we are required to determine if Thrice Corp.'s cash went up or down for the following information given in the problem.","images":{"latex":{"large":{"height":66,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/21/12/29/a1d98dc79d17aedda96eb3cd6f18ba14/a2ef24e00f699ddb862e46b385453851/lateximg_large.png","width":996},"regular":{"height":34,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/21/12/29/a1d98dc79d17aedda96eb3cd6f18ba14/a2ef24e00f699ddb862e46b385453851/lateximg.png","width":497}},"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":true}],"isResult":false,"stepNumber":1},{"columns":[{"text":"Before we begin, let us first define operating activity.\n\n**Operating activity** is a section of a company's cash flow statement that shows the amount of money a company brings in from its regular business activities.\n\n","images":{"latex":{"large":{"height":135,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/21/12/29/a1d98dc79d17aedda96eb3cd6f18ba14/e7725d72723be415ed9e956a6f110859/lateximg_large.png","width":995},"regular":{"height":69,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/21/12/29/a1d98dc79d17aedda96eb3cd6f18ba14/e7725d72723be415ed9e956a6f110859/lateximg.png","width":497}},"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":false}],"isResult":false,"stepNumber":2},{"columns":[{"text":"The **indirect method** is the most common method of reconciling net income to net cash flow from operating activities. \n\n","images":{"latex":{"large":{"height":68,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/21/12/29/a1d98dc79d17aedda96eb3cd6f18ba14/3ba5f6a48a17c4ed9a04f025bd30e2de/lateximg_large.png","width":995},"regular":{"height":34,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/21/12/29/a1d98dc79d17aedda96eb3cd6f18ba14/3ba5f6a48a17c4ed9a04f025bd30e2de/lateximg.png","width":497}},"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":false}],"isResult":false,"stepNumber":3},{"columns":[{"text":"To determine if the cash went up or down, add or subtract all increases and decreases in current assets or current liability accounts based on their cash impact. \n$$\\begin{array}{l r}\\\\\n\\text{Decrease in inventory} & \\text{\\$375}\\\\\n\\text{Less: Decrease in accounts payable} & \\text{220}\\\\\n\\text{Add: Increase in notes payable} & \\text{290}\\\\ \n\\text{Less: Increase in accounts receivable} & \\text{270}\\\\ \\hline\n\\textbf{Increase (Decrease) in cash} & \\underline{\\underline{\\$175}}\\\\ \\\\\n\\end{array}$$\n\nIn conclusion, there is an increase in cash of $175.","images":{"latex":null,"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":false}],"isResult":false,"stepNumber":4},{"columns":[{"text":"$175","images":{"latex":null,"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":false}],"isResult":true,"stepNumber":5}],"rating":5,"solutionUuid":"605e99e8-7e97-4716-a2db-320d4fb9dbee","editorVersion":2,"answeredOn":null,"ratingCount":null,"solutionOrder":null,"totalSteps":5}],"textbook":{"authors":"Bradford D. Jordan, Randolph W. Westerfield, Stephen A. Ross","imageUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/textbook_covers/tmpm0p82b7h","imageThumbnailUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/cache/d1/d3/d1d34d106dd29dd2e71be582412ef59d.jpg","id":34320,"isbn":"9781259918957","isPremium":true,"title":"Fundamentals of Corporate Finance","edition":"12th Edition","verifiedSolutionCount":1217,"shouldBeIndexableForSeo":true,"modified":1665448474394,"active":true,"publisher":"McGraw-Hill Education","mainTextbookIsbn":null,"subjects":{"level1":["Social Science"],"level2":["Economics"],"level3":["Finance"]}},"nextE